\f0\fs24 \cf0 \b Sainte-Barbe\b0 \
\
A small coastal village on the northern shore, population approximately eight hundred. Built on a rocky promontory above a crescent harbor, the village is flanked by limestone cliffs that drop sharply into the sea to the east and slope into gravel beaches to the west.\
\
Key landmarks: the Church of Saint Barbara (12th century, partially restored), one primary school, the post office, and Marguerite\'92s bookshop on Rue de la Chapelle. The harbor supports a small fishing fleet\'97mostly sole and mackerel. A single bus connects the village to the nearest town, forty kilometers south.\
\
The climate is wet and cool, with fog common from October through March. The village is quiet in winter and modestly busy in summer, when a handful of tourists come for the cliff walks.}